
[1]foam

   FOAM, n. [L. fumo, to smoke, to foam.]

   Froth; spume; the substance which is formed on the surface of liquors
   by fermentation or violent agitation, consisting of bubbles.

                                 FOAM, v.i.

   1. To froth; to gather foam. The billows foam. A horse foams at the
   mouth when violently heated.

   2. To be in a rage; to be violently agitated.

   He foameth and gnasheth with his teeth. Mark 9.

          FOAM, v.t. To throw out with rage or violence; with out.

   Foaming out their own shame. Jude 13.
